[4/21/94 public]
It is not a password.  Keyseed really is a good word for it.  You type this
in once to sec_create_db and never have to know it again.  Writing it down
would be a bad thing.  The registry is a principal and encrypts it's data
in a key.  To get the whole ball rolling it needs an initial random value,
which it turns into a key.

The keyseed should just be random junk.  It's probably better if it's
nothing that you can remember (like a password).

[4/21/94 public]

When I used the word "password" I was thinking of another attribute of
a password: that it should not be easy to guess. It certainly seems that 
this ought to be an attribute of the "keyseed" as well. I can see Howard's
point that other attributes of a password come to mind that should not be
characteristics of the keyseed but I do think that there should be a word
in the documentation about not selecting an easily guessed string (I use
"qwerty" all the time ;)) as the keyseed.

[04/21/94 public]
You know ksh has the $RANDOM variable...  I've always though doing
	if [ "x$RANDOM" -eq "x$RANDOM ] ; then
	    ...ask for a random text string for initial key...
